<Document>
<name>Captain Cook Highway &amp; Cape Tribulation</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Captain Cook Highway &amp; Cape Tribulation</h2><p><i>Queensland, Australia · Cairns to Cape Tribulation</i></p><p><b>The only place on Earth where two World Heritage Areas meet at the road — Great Barrier Reef offshore, Daintree Rainforest at the windscreen.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>113 km (70 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3 hrs without stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–October dry season; wet season (Nov–Apr) brings rain, stingers, road closures</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Saltwater crocodiles in coastal rivers; box jellyfish in summer (Nov–May); cassowaries on road north of Daintree; wet-season closures</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>165</td></tr></table><hr><p>Two UNESCO World Heritage Areas meet here — the world's largest coral reef ecosystem on one side, the world's oldest continuously surviving rainforest (135 million years) on the other. North of Cairns the Captain Cook Highway runs along a knife-edge coastline of headlands and coral-sand beaches to Port Douglas. Beyond Mossman, you cross the Daintree River by cable ferry into a different country — World Heritage rainforest with the southern cassowary still present (you may meet one on the road; do not approach), and the road ends abruptly at Cape Tribulation, named by Cook in June 1770 because his ship struck a reef just offshore. Past the Cape, the unsealed Bloomfield Track requires 4WD and is often closed.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Palm Cove</b> — Esplanade lined with melaleuca paperbarks — the kind of street where you can stand on the curb and feel the breeze under the canopy.</li><li><b>Rex Lookout</b> — Pull-off above a long curve of rainforest-backed beach, the postcard view looking north. Hang gliders launch on a strong southeasterly.</li><li><b>Port Douglas</b> — Deluxe Reef-and-rainforest base. Quicksilver and other operators run day trips to the outer reef from the marina; Four Mile Beach is patrolled and stinger-netted in summer.</li><li><b>Mossman Gorge</b> — Kuku Yalanji land — Indigenous-led Dreamtime walks. Granite-floored swimming holes; the gorge boardwalk loop is wheelchair accessible.</li><li><b>Daintree River cable ferry</b> — 5-minute crossing, no booking. Saltwater crocodiles regularly seen from the deck — boat tours from the upstream side go specifically to find them.</li><li><b>Cow Bay</b> — First proper beach in the Daintree section. The Discovery Centre 1 km south has an aerial walkway through the rainforest canopy.</li><li><b>Cape Tribulation</b> — End of the sealed road. The headland looks out over the reef where Cook's HMS Endeavour holed itself on a coral bommie in June 1770. Beach swimming OK only in the dry season.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
